On Friday 08 June 2007 16:56, John Goerzen wrote:
> On Thu, Jun 07, 2007 at 11:57:22PM +0200, Kern Sibbald wrote:
> > However, I have now removed *all* modifications, so that the current 
Bacula 
> > code as of a few hours ago has no modifications to GPL v2.  I am attaching 
a 
> > copy of the current LICENSE file as it is at this moment in the SVN
> 
> I'm not quite following; what modifications have you removed here?

Sorry, I was not very clear.  I have removed all modifications to the GPL v2 
license.  The current Bacula code is licensed GPL v2 without any 
modifications.  

Some of the text that was previously modifications to the GPL license is now 
included as notes from the developers for information only.

> 
> Is this still current, BTW?  In a later message you mentioned changing
> the OpenSSL exemption to a "note frmo the author", but still in the
> LICENSE file.  I wonder if Debian could consider that legally
> sufficient?

I cannot comment on what is legally sufficient for Debian, but I can say as 
author of Bacula and not speaking for the approx 10-20 files copyrighted by 
3rd parties that for me there is no problem linking with OpenSSL.  However, 
for the reasons I previously noted, I cannot make that a modification of the 
license.

Just so there is no confusion, I have attached the current LICENSE file -- 
although there are now some notes or comments from the developers (which are 
most likely not legally binding), there are now no modifications to the GPL.  
Perhaps the confusion is that not every word in our LICENSE file is part of 
the actual license given -- for example the section History: is clearly not 
part of the license, as well as the part under Linking: ...   If this is not 
clear after having read the LICENSE file, please let me know.

Regards,

Kern

